# Veylix — UX Requirements (MVP)

**Pre-trade risk visibility for retail crypto.** Veylix shows a retail investor how buying, selling, holding, or hedging reshapes the *distribution* of where their portfolio could land — before they act. It is an **education and transparency tool, not an advice tool**: it surfaces and explains risk in plain language and never recommends a position.

Status: hackathon MVP · single-page web app (desktop-first, responsive to mobile) · Encode / BGA AI Trading & Strategy track. **This doc reflects the current build** (see the standalone HTML in the repo and §13). Where the build already meets a requirement it's noted; the open gaps are concentrated in §10 (accessibility) and §11 (acceptance criteria).

---

## 1. Scope

**In scope (MVP)**
- One screen, no navigation. All interaction is live recalculation, not page transitions.
- A sample portfolio the user edits via sliders (no wallet/exchange connection yet).
- Client-side Monte Carlo risk simulation (~3,000 paths) with a fixed seed.
- Plain-language explanation of every number shown, in both % and dollar terms.

**Non-goals (explicitly out for MVP)**
- No investment advice or recommendations. No "you should" anywhere.
- No trade execution, custody, or order routing.
- No login/auth, no persistence, no real portfolio/exchange data.
- No price prediction. We model risk and dispersion, not expected returns.

---

## 2. Primary user & guiding principle

**User:** an experienced, risk-tolerant retail crypto investor. They already take volatile positions in one tap; what they lack is the pre-trade risk visibility institutions take for granted.

**Job to be done:** *"Before I act, show me how this move changes my downside — in terms I can actually read."*

**Guiding UX principle:** every element on the screen must close a specific information gap between this user and an institution. If a component doesn't reduce that gap or help the user read their risk, cut it.

---

## 3. Core interaction (the spine)

This is the one flow that must feel effortless; everything else supports it.

1. **First load** — the screen opens populated: "Current" portfolio preset, 30-day horizon, 0% hedge. The outcome cone, the worst-case figures, and all five stat tiles are already rendered. No empty state, no "click to begin," no spinner beyond a flash.
2. **Adjust** — the user drags an allocation slider, the BTC hedge slider, the funding rate, or changes horizon.
3. **See the consequence** — the cone, the worst-case/median figures, the five tiles, and the "Why these numbers" sentence all recompute together, live.

**The demo moment (must land):** with "Current" loaded, dragging the BTC hedge slider up visibly pulls the coral downside tail *upward* while the median line barely moves. The "1-in-20" number — in both % and dollars — improves in real time. Switching presets (Current → Balanced) teaches the same lesson for diversification. This single interaction is the pitch — protect the bad case, and see what it costs.

---

## 4. Information architecture (single screen)

Top to bottom on desktop; controls drop below the chart on mobile.

1. **Header** — Veylix wordmark + an "Educational · not investment advice" pill + a **portfolio-value pill** + a one-line lede.
2. **Outcome cone** (hero, ~60% of screen width on desktop), with the worst-case and median figures pinned above it.
3. **Controls panel** (right of cone on desktop, stacked below on mobile).
4. **Stat tiles** — a row of five.
5. **"Why these numbers"** — the live explanation panel.
6. **Footer** — full disclaimer.

Responsive: single column below ~860px. Cone full-width, then controls, then tiles (2-up), then explanation. Usable down to 375px.

---

## 5. Component requirements

### 5.0 Header
- **Wordmark:** "Veylix" with a two-tone treatment — "Vey" in ink, "lix" in amber — beside a small logo mark slot.
- **Educational pill:** "Educational · not investment advice" with an amber dot. Always visible.
- **Portfolio-value pill:** the total portfolio value (e.g. "$24,860 portfolio"). This value is the **basis for every dollar figure on screen** (worst-case $, the right-hand chart axis). Should be user-settable so the dollar amounts reflect the user's own portfolio size; defaults to a sample value.
- **Lede:** "You can buy, sell, or hold in one tap — see the consequence first. Veylix shows how a move reshapes your downside before you make it."

### 5.1 Outcome cone (the hero)
- Monte Carlo distribution of portfolio value over the horizon, drawn as percentile bands (5 / 25 / 50 / 75 / 95) across time. Hand-rendered on Canvas 2D at device-pixel resolution.
- **Semantic encoding:** downside band (5th–25th) tinted coral; middle band (25th–75th) neutral; upper band (75th–95th) tinted teal. Median (50th) as an amber line. The 5th-percentile boundary drawn as a distinct coral line with an endpoint dot.
- A dashed horizontal reference line at the starting value (break-even).
- **Pinned figures above the chart:**
  - Eyebrow: "1-IN-20 WORST CASE · [horizon]".
  - The worst-case return shown **large, in coral** — the number the eye lands on first.
  - A human-readable sub-line pairing it with dollars: e.g. "A bad month — your portfolio could fall to $15,485" (see §7 for the horizon→phrase mapping).
  - **Median** shown top-right of the chart, labelled, **in amber** (e.g. "MEDIAN −4%").
- **Dual axis:** **% return on the left** (e.g. +55% / +30% / +5% / −20% / −45%) and the **equivalent dollar value on the right** (the same percentages applied to the portfolio value). The two must stay consistent.
- X-axis: "today → Nd".
- Caption: methodology + sim count, e.g. "~3,000 simulated paths · zero-drift volatility model — risk, not prediction".

### 5.2 Portfolio: presets + allocation sliders
- Three preset buttons: **Current** (concentrated/high-risk, the default), **Balanced**, **BTC-heavy**, under a "PRESET" label ("starting points"). Selecting one sets all allocations and visibly marks itself active (amber fill).
- Five allocation sliders under an "ALLOCATION" label ("% of portfolio"): BTC, ETH, SOL, Mid-cap alt, Microcap/meme. Each row carries a small **asset-identity swatch** and shows its current **% share**. Editing any slider deselects the active preset (user is now "Custom").
- Shares are normalised to 100% for the model; display the normalised %.
- **Colour guardrail:** asset swatches (BTC amber, ETH periwinkle, SOL mint, Mid-cap violet, Microcap coral) identify assets; the chart's coral/teal carry *meaning* (downside/upside). Keep swatches small and quiet so a coral asset dot never reads as "downside" or a mint dot as "upside." Identity and semantics must not blur.

### 5.3 BTC hedge slider
- Range 0–100%. Represents the share of the portfolio's net BTC-beta exposure offset by a short-BTC position.
- Styled in the amber accent (it's the protective lever — visually distinct from allocations).
- Label and value both in amber.
- **Helper microcopy** beneath it: "A short BTC position that offsets market-wide moves. Drag it up and watch the coral downside tail lift — while the median barely moves."

### 5.4 Hedge funding rate + carry readout
- A slider directly beneath the hedge slider (they are a pair), annualised %. Range ≈ −25% to +75%/yr, default **+10%/yr**.
- Labelled as the **carry cost of holding the BTC short**, with a one-line note: *positive = you pay to hold the hedge; negative = funding favours shorts and you're paid to hold it.*
- Beneath it, a live readout: **"Hedge carry over [horizon]: ±X.X%"** — **coral when it's a cost, teal when it's a credit** — the cumulative funding drag/credit as a % of the portfolio over the selected horizon.
- Teaching point this exists to surface: hedge economics depend on funding. A high funding rate erodes the benefit of hedging; over-hedging in an expensive-funding regime bleeds the median. This is a real institutional asymmetry made visible.

### 5.5 Horizon toggle
- Segmented control: 7d / 30d / 90d. Default 30d. Changes the simulation horizon, the carry window, and the worst-case phrasing.

### 5.6 Stat tiles (five)
Each tile is a label + a large monospace number. Each must have a plain-language explanation available (tooltip or inline) of what it means, in user terms.

| Tile | Meaning shown to the user | Colour |
|---|---|---|
| Median outcome | Your most-likely result over the horizon | neutral (ink) |
| 1-in-20 downside | A typical bad day — worse than this 5% of the time | coral |
| Typical max drawdown | The biggest peak-to-trough drop along the way | coral |
| Chance of losing >25% | How often a quarter or more is wiped out | neutral (ink) |
| Effective BTC beta | How hard your portfolio still moves with BTC after hedging | amber |

### 5.7 "Why these numbers" panel
- A live, plain-language sentence (not a static blurb). Rules for what it must say:
  - Name the **biggest risk driver** (the asset contributing most volatility) and its share.
  - When a hedge is on, state what it does to the downside floor *and* its carry cost at the current funding rate — e.g. *"The 50% hedge lifts your 1-in-20 floor from −42% to −31%, but at +10%/yr funding it carries a ~0.9% cost over 30 days, trimming your median."*
  - When no hedge is on, name the unhedged BTC-beta exposure and invite the user to try the hedge slider.
- Rewrites itself whenever any input changes. Key figures emphasised inline (downside in coral, hedge/funding in amber).

### 5.8 Disclaimer
- Footer, visible without scrolling on desktop. Must contain the words **"not investment advice."** Exact wording in §7.

