## 9. Transparency & trust UX (the BGA differentiator)

This is a scoring lever, not just polish. The product must *look and feel* auditable and honest:
- **Methodology is always on screen** (the caption), never hidden.
- **Every number is explained** in plain language and in dollars (the "Why" panel + tile explanations + the worst-case sub-line) — no unexplained black-box outputs.
- **Honest trade-offs:** hedging shows its *cost* (the carry readout), not only its benefit. The tool never implies a free lunch.
- **No-advice framing is surfaced**, not buried in a ToS — the header pill and footer make the posture visible.
- (Roadmap, ties to Sui track) Storing each simulation run — inputs, seed, output distribution — so any readout is independently reproducible would make the risk numbers verifiable, not just transparent.

---

## 10. Accessibility & quality floor

- Full keyboard operability: every slider, toggle, and preset reachable and operable by keyboard, with visible focus rings.
- Respect `prefers-reduced-motion` (no entrance/transition animation when set).
- Contrast meets WCAG AA for text and key UI against the dark background.
- Canvas chart needs a non-visual equivalent: expose the key figures (worst case, median, drawdown) as readable text near the chart, not only as pixels.
- Responsive and usable down to 375px width.
- No layout jitter: tabular figures, fixed control widths — numbers update in place.
- Compute never blocks scrolling or input.

---

## 11. Acceptance criteria (Definition of Done)

- [ ] First load is fully populated (Current / 30d / 0% hedge) — cone + worst-case/median + all five tiles rendered, no spinner beyond a flash.
- [ ] Any input change updates the cone, the worst-case/median figures, all tiles, and the "Why" sentence together, in place, without width jitter.
- [ ] On "Current", dragging hedge 0→100% visibly raises the coral downside tail and improves the "1-in-20" number (% and $); median moves only slightly.
- [ ] Funding rate changes the carry readout's magnitude and sign; a negative rate flips it to a teal credit and the explanation follows.
- [ ] The right-hand dollar axis and worst-case dollar figure stay consistent with the stated portfolio value.
- [ ] Worst-case sub-line uses the correct horizon phrase (week / month / quarter).
- [ ] Every stat tile exposes a plain-language explanation of what it means.
- [ ] "Why these numbers" names the top risk driver and the hedge's effect + cost, and updates live.
- [ ] Disclaimer is visible without scrolling on desktop and contains "not investment advice."
- [ ] Fully keyboard-operable with visible focus; respects reduced motion; key figures available as text (not canvas-only); usable at 375px.
- [ ] Fixed seed: identical inputs → identical cone (no re-render jitter).

---

## 12. Out of scope now / next

- Connect real holdings (wallet address via WalletConnect, or Bybit account import) to replace the sample sliders.
- Per-asset on-chain risk flags (liquidity depth, holder concentration) for the long-tail assets.
- Persisted scenarios / shareable risk snapshots.
- On-chain auditability of simulation runs (Walrus) and self-directed hedge execution (DeepBook) — only if the core lands first.

---

## 13. Implementation (as built)

Framework-free core, no build step, no backend — it all runs in the browser.

- **Vanilla JavaScript + HTML + CSS** for the whole dashboard (sim, controls, live recompute), kept framework-free so the Monte Carlo recompute stays fast on every slider drag.
- **HTML5 Canvas 2D** for the outcome cone — hand-drawn percentile bands, lines, and endpoint dot, redrawn each frame at device-pixel resolution.
- **CSS custom properties** for the whole theme, so colours/fonts/panel styles can be swapped live.
- **Google Fonts** — Space Grotesk (headings), Manrope (body), JetBrains Mono (tabular numbers).
- **React + Babel** only for the small Tweaks panel (visual-style toggles) — not the app itself.

**File structure**
- `veylix-sim.js` — seeded Monte Carlo engine.
- `veylix-chart.js` — Canvas renderer.
- `veylix-app.js` — UI wiring.
- `veylix-tweaks.jsx` — Tweaks panel.
- `Veylix.html` — loads it all; the standalone export inlines everything into one offline file.

**Model summary** (detail lives with `veylix-sim.js`)
- ~3,000 paths, fixed seed, zero-drift (models risk/dispersion, not returns).
- Assets share a common BTC market factor plus idiosyncratic noise; a BTC hedge shorts the common factor (cutting variance) and carries a funding cost. Detailed factor betas and per-asset vols should be documented alongside the engine for verifiability.
